<h2 align="center" style="font-style:italic;font-weight:normal;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;page-break-after:auto;text-align:center;"><b><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:normal;font-weight:bold;">An Ohio Corporation</font></i></b></h2>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">I.R.S. Employer
Identification No. 31-1458309</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">3939 International Gateway</font></b></p>

principal executive offices) (Zip Code)</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(Registrant&#146;s

<p align="right" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

registered pursuant to Section 12(b) of the Act:</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc. common shares, $.01 par value,
are registered on the New York Stock Exchange</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;text-indent:.5in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Indicate by check mark

  </td>
 </tr>
 <tr>
  <td width="18%" colspan="2" valign="top" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:18.54%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt 60.0pt;text-indent:-10.0pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;"><a href="#Item7a" title="Click to goto ITEM 7A">Item
  7A:</a></font></p>
  </td>
  <td width="81%" valign="top" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:81.46%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;"><a href="#Item7a" title="Click to goto ITEM 7A">Quantitative and
  Qualitative Disclosures about Market Risk</a></font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>

  8:</a></font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">2</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='2',FILE='C:\C2\ahanson\8404_4\t_1322525\j8404_10k.htm',USER='ahanson',CD='Mar 26 15:16 2003' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">&nbsp;</font></b></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><a name="PartI"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">PART
I</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item1Business"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 1 -
BUSINESS</font></b></a></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">General</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc. is a
specialty air carrier for time-sensitive deliveries, operating between 100 U.S.
cities and delivering over 20,000 time-critical shipments each working
day.&#160; AirNet&#146;s Bank service, which
generates approximately 68% of AirNet&#146;s revenues, is the leading transporter of
cancelled checks and related information for the U.S. banking industry, meeting
more than 2,200 daily deadlines.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s Express service,
which generates approximately 29% of AirNet&#146;s revenues, provides specialized,
high-priority delivery services.&#160; In
December 2002, AirNet was awarded a General Services Administration Federal Supply
Schedule, Indefinite Delivery/Indefinite Quantity contract to provide domestic
express delivery services to U.S. federal government agencies.&#160; This contract will allow us to provide
specialized, highly sensitive, and expedited transportation solutions to
various governmental agencies at pre-negotiated rates.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s Aviation
services product line, which accounts for approximately 3% of AirNet&#146;s
revenues, began offering a broader array of passenger charter services in 2002.
Through the use of seven passenger-configured Learjets, passenger charters are
offered 24 hours per day, seven days per week. This product line also offers
on-demand cargo charters, retail aviation fuel sales and related ground
services to customers in Columbus, Ohio.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In addition to the seven
passenger-configured Learjets, AirNet operates a fleet of 122 aircraft (33
Learjets, 15 Cessna Caravans and 74 light twin engine aircraft), that fly
approximately 120,000 miles per operating night, primarily Monday through
Thursday.&#160; On-demand cargo charter
services are offered 24 hours per day, seven days per week.&#160; AirNet also provides ground pick-up and
delivery services throughout the nation seven days per week, using a
combination of company personnel and a network of approximately 250 vendors and
independent contractors.&#160; AirNet&#146;s
integrated air and ground network provides support for our base customers,
primarily concentrated in the banking, medical and critical parts industries.&#160; AirNet also uses commercial airlines to
provide same-day delivery service for some of our Bank service and Express
service customers.&#160; Later pick-ups and
earlier deliveries than those offered by other national carriers are the
differentiating characteristics of AirNet&#146;s time-critical delivery
network.&#160; AirNet uses a number of
proprietary customer service and management information systems to track, sort,
dispatch and control the flow of checks and small packages throughout AirNet&#146;s
delivery system.&#160; Delivery times and
selected shipment information are available on-line through the Internet.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Systems, Inc. was
incorporated as a C-corporation under the laws of the State of Ohio on
February&nbsp;15, 1996.&#160; AirNet&#146;s
principal executive offices are located at 3939&nbsp;International Gateway,
Columbus, Ohio 43219, and our telephone number is (614) 237-9777.&#160; AirNet&#146;s web site address is </font>www.airnet.com (this uniform resource
location (URL) is an inactive textual reference only and is not intended to
incorporate our website into this report).</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Business strategy</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">We will continue to
pursue our multi-year strategy to transform AirNet into a company that
maximizes utilization of its unique airline by responding to growth
opportunities for our Express business, while also continuing to respond to the
needs of our bank customers.&#160; This
diversification will likely require significant changes in our route structure
and a greater investment in sales and marketing during the transition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">We are adapting to
changes in the banking industry by reconfiguring our operational structure and
its associated costs to align it with the volume and revenue changes.&#160; We have also developed a new pricing model
for our major bank customers to attract greater volumes and benefit both AirNet
and our bank customers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Our Express customers
value our speed and customer service, and AirNet intends to focus on
time-critical markets, and time-definite delivery markets such as medical,
radioactive pharmaceutical, on-demand cargo charters and just-in-time
inventories, in which our airline offers customers competitive advantages in
their industries through our speed and customer service.&#160; We believe our flexible and reliable air
network and demonstrated expertise in providing time-critical deliveries to the
banking industry for over 28 years positions us to provide these expanded
services to the Express market.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">3</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='3',FILE='C:\C2\ahanson\8404_4\t_1322525\j8404_10k.htm',USER='ahanson',CD='Mar 26 15:16 2003' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Product lines</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet provides its
services under 3 product lines:&#160; Bank
services, Express services and Aviation services.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Bank
services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Bank services primarily
consist of cancelled check delivery.&#160;
AirNet also transports items, such as proof of delivery reports and
interoffice mail, for many of the same Bank customers.&#160; AirNet has historically priced its Bank
services based on the tier of service, and by the pound, on a
customer-by-customer basis.&#160; The U.S.
banking industry, including commercial banks, savings banks and Federal Reserve
banks, represents AirNet&#146;s largest category of customers and accounted for
approximately 68% of our revenues in 2002, 75% in 2001 and 74% in 2000. This
customer list represents over 100 of the nation&#146;s largest bank holding
companies.&#160; AirNet&#146;s time-critical
cancelled check delivery service allows our banking customers to offer
competitive products and pricing.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Express
services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Express revenues
accounted for 29% of AirNet&#146;s revenues in 2002, 24% in 2001 and 26% in
2000.&#160; Within Express services, AirNet
has several product offerings including Medical, Air Courier, Retail and
Mercury Business Services.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Medical services are
offered to customers requiring specialized handling, the transportation of
which is often highly regulated by varying governmental authorities.&#160; Targeted markets within medical include
producers and recipients of radioactive pharmaceuticals, diagnostic specimens,
blood, human tissue and organs.&#160; AirNet
also provides passenger charter services to organ transplant teams requiring
time-critical travel to donor/recipient medical centers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Air courier services
provide transportation solutions to forwarders, integrators and courier
companies.&#160; AirNet provides late-night
services beyond most integrators&#146; and forwarders&#146; deadlines.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Retail services are
provided to end consumers whose shipment needs are highly time sensitive or
time definite.&#160; Target markets include
just-in-time manufacturers and critical parts suppliers.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Mercury Business Services
provides nationwide overnight delivery from the Boston, Chicago and New York
metropolitan areas.&#160; Shipments are
picked up by a Mercury courier, processed and then forwarded to a third party
carrier to transport and deliver.&#160;
Target markets include law firms and small professional services firms
in dense business districts.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Aviation
services</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Aviation services
product line was expanded in 2001 to increase utilization of our airline beyond
historical nighttime flights and to capitalize on our aircraft maintenance
expertise.&#160; The Aviation services
product line offers passenger charter services, on-demand cargo charters, and
operates a fixed base operation from our Columbus, Ohio facility, offering
retail aviation fuel sales and related ground services.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Delivery service offerings</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet provides the
following types of delivery service:&#160;
ANX (transported via the AirNet airline), AMC (AirNet Mission Critical),
SDX (transported via third-party carriers), ground-only and on-demand cargo
charter.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">ANX
service</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s ANX service is
designed around three sets of deadlines. Basic deadlines, which have a hub time
in Columbus between 9:30 p.m. and 10:00 p.m., provide delivery service between
12:01 a.m. and 2:00 a.m. to approximately the northeastern third of the
nation.&#160; Premium deadlines, which have a
hub time between 11:00 p.m. and 11:30 p.m. in Columbus and Charlotte, provide
delivery service at approximately 3:00 a.m. to the eastern half of the
nation.&#160; Finally, City deadlines, which
have a hub time in Columbus between 4:00 a.m. and 5:30 a.m., provide delivery
service at approximately 8:00 a.m. to all cities served by the network.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Bank ANX shipments are
pre-sorted by bank personnel and packaged in AirNet-supplied bags color-coded
to easily identify the final destination.&#160;
ANX Express shipments are packaged in either AirNet-provided packaging
or the customers&#146; packaging.&#160; An ANX
shipment is typically picked up by an AirNet courier and transported to the
local airport where the airbill is scanned using bar code technology, and
information pertaining to the shipper, receiver, airbill number and applicable
deadline is captured. This data is then downloaded into AirNet&#146;s ComCheck or
AirNet Connect computer system, where it is available to AirNet&#146;s customer
service representatives (&#147;CSRs&#148;).</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">4</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='4',FILE='C:\C2\ahanson\8404_4\t_1322525\j8404_10k.htm',USER='ahanson',CD='Mar 26 15:16 2003' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Upon arrival at AirNet&#146;s
Columbus hub or one of our mini-hubs, the shipment is off-loaded, sorted by destination
and reloaded onto an aircraft. At the destination city, the shipment is
off-loaded for the final time and delivered by courier to the receiver.&#160; When delivered, the airbill is once again
scanned and delivery information is downloaded into AirNet&#146;s computer system.
Delivery information for all shipments is then available on-line to the
customers and CSRs.&#160; AirNet&#146;s customer
service department is available to handle any inquiries, discrepancies or
supply requests, as well as provide proof of delivery documentation, all of
which are value-added features of AirNet&#146;s service.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">AMC
service</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet Mission Critical
service is available when customers require enhanced levels of special care in
chain of custody, communications, or operating controls on their ANX shipments.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">SDX
service</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s SDX service
provides cancelled check delivery services to Bank customers meeting daytime
banking deadlines, and to Express customers requiring next-flight-out timing.
These shipments are typically picked up by AirNet couriers and transported via
commercial airlines or other integrators to destination cities where couriers
accept the packages and deliver them to the destinations.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Ground
only</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Ground only services are
provided to customers with specialized handling requirements that match
AirNet&#146;s unique delivery capabilities in select markets.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">On-demand
cargo charter</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On-demand cargo charter
services are provided to customers requiring the full use of an aircraft for
dedicated deliveries.&#160; Charters may be
scheduled in advance or on an as-needed basis.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Passenger
charter services</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s private charter
service provides travelers a safe, fast, and convenient way to travel.&#160; Private charter service is available 24
hours a day, 7 days a week primarily within the continental United States and
neighboring countries.&#160;&#160; In addition to
serving retail customers, AirNet provides charter services through third-party
charter brokers.&#160; AirNet operates its
private charter service from four locations across the country (Columbus, Dallas,
Lancaster, PA and Bedford, MA).&#160; All
passenger charter pilots are Airline Transport Pilot rated &#150; the highest </font>Federal Aviation Administration (&#147;FAA&#148;) rating
possible.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Operations</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Airline capacity management</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Capacity management is an
important factor in achieving profitable growth of the company.&#160; The airline is positioned around a flexible
national route structure designed to facilitate late pick-up and early delivery
times, minimize delays and simplify flight scheduling.&#160; AirNet&#146;s hub-and-spoke system, with a
primary hub in Columbus, Ohio and several mini-hubs across the nation (Atlanta,
Chicago, Charlotte, Dallas, Denver, Des Moines and New York), allows AirNet to
match the varying load capacities of our aircraft with the shipment weight and
volume of each destination city and to consolidate shipments at our hubs. The
hubs are located primarily in less congested regional airports. These
locations, in conjunction with AirNet&#146;s off-peak departure and arrival times,
provide easy take-off and landings, convenient loading and unloading, and fast
refueling and maintenance.&#160; Volume load
factors by aircraft, departure city-pairs and lane segments are key
contributors to profitability, as is the mix of aircraft and overall fleet
utilization.&#160; Scales and scanners have
been installed in some of our customer&#146;s facilities in order to capture weight
on an end-point basis. This data allows us to create point-to-point routes on
specific lane segments, where appropriate, which reduces excess capacity in the
hub-and-spoke route system.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Aircraft maintenance</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet employs aircraft
and avionics technicians in eight separate locations across the country
(Columbus, Dallas, Denver, Hartford, Minneapolis, New Orleans, Birmingham and
Philadelphia), performing all levels of maintenance from 100-hour inspections
on our light twin-engine aircraft to 7,200-hour/12-year inspections on our
fleet of Learjets.&#160; AirNet has an
in-house engine shop at the Columbus facility where some of the piston engines
are overhauled on-site, thereby reducing aircraft downtime and controlling
costs.&#160; AirNet also performs avionics
troubleshooting and repair at the Columbus facility to provide for maximum
efficiency and minimum aircraft downtime for the fleet.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">5</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='5',FILE='C:\C2\ahanson\8404_4\t_1322525\j8404_10k.htm',USER='ahanson',CD='Mar 26 15:16 2003' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Flight operations</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s flight
operations are headquartered in Columbus, Ohio.&#160; AirNet utilizes an extensive screening process to evaluate
potential pilots prior to hiring. These pilots meet stringent company
qualifications, as well as all required Federal Aviation Administration
requirements.&#160; All new pilots must
satisfactorily complete a five-week training program conducted by AirNet&#146;s
flight training staff prior to assignment of pilot duties.&#160; This training program includes flight
simulator training prior to any actual flight time in an aircraft, as well as
intensive ground instruction.&#160; </font>Additionally, new pilots gain operating experience in a structured&nbsp;setting prior to assignment in order to gain
a familiarity with AirNet&#146;s route system and the unique demands of&nbsp;the flight environment.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet&#146;s central dispatch
system ties together all components of the air operation. Departure and arrival
times are continuously updated, and weather conditions throughout the nation
are constantly monitored. AirNet dispatchers remain in constant contact with
pilots, out-based hub managers, fuelers, maintenance technicians and ground
delivery personnel to ensure that no gaps exist in the delivery process.&#160; AirNet also uses commercial airlines,
primarily to transport shipments during the daytime and weekend hours when our
aircraft are operating under a limited flight schedule.&#160; Operations personnel utilize <i><font style="font-style:italic;">FlightTrax, </font></i>a
computerized flight tracking system that allows them to track the status of
every AirNet and commercial flight in the country and schedule ground pick-up
and delivery personnel appropriately.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Ground operations</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet manages its ground
services through a combined use of employed team member couriers and
approximately 250 outside independent contractor and vendor couriers.&#160; Team members are typically utilized on the
scheduled routes that occur each operational day.&#160; Independent contractors and vendors are typically used for ad hoc
pick-up and delivery services, allowing us to better match our ground costs
with our volume streams.&#160; Dispatching
functions related to ground delivery services occur at both the Columbus, Ohio
hub and on a regional basis in some of the major cities served.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Shipments are typically
picked up by a courier and delivered to the originating airport where AirNet
ground support personnel load the shipments into aircraft. Upon arrival at the
main hub in Columbus, Ohio, packages are off-loaded, sorted by destination and
reloaded onto aircraft.&#160; During the
thirty to forty minute sort period, AirNet ground support personnel refuel the
aircraft.&#160; Fueling operations in
Columbus include trained fuelers and ground support equipment, including seven
fuel trucks and approximately 86,500 gallons of fuel storage capacity.&#160; Contracted fixed base operators at local
airports typically perform out-based fueling of aircraft.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Regulation</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet holds an air
carrier certificate granted by </font>the FAA pursuant to Part 135 of the Federal Aviation Regulations.
This certificate is of unlimited duration and remains in effect so long as
AirNet maintains its standards of safety and meets the operational requirements
of the regulations.&#160; The FAA&#146;s
regulatory authority relates primarily to operational aspects of air transportation,
including aircraft standards and maintenance, personnel and ground facilities.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In
August 2002, the FAA issued rules mandating repairs on certain Piper Navajo
aircraft.&#160; The ruling, </font>in response to incidents experienced by
other owners involving the aircraft&#146;s crankshaft, immediately grounded the
aircraft until the mandated repairs were made.&#160;
AirNet&#146;s airline fleet currently includes two such grounded aircraft (seven as of December 31,
2002), which will remain grounded until replacement engines or repair parts
become available.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
U. S. Department of Transportation (&#147;DOT&#148;) and Transportation Security
Administration (&#147;TSA&#148;) have regulatory authority concerning operational and
security concerns in transportation, respectively, including safety, insurance
and hazardous materials.&#160; AirNet holds
various operational certificates issued by these agencies, including party
status to DOT E-7060, which permits AirNet to transport specific volumes of
time-critical radioactive pharmaceuticals.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
is also subject to Food and Drug Administration regulation of our
transportation of pharmaceuticals.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In
addition to federal regulations, AirNet&#146;s operations are subject to various
state and local regulations, and in many instances, require permits and
licenses from state authorities.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman"><font style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet
believes that we have all permits, approvals and licenses required to conduct
our operations and that we are in compliance with applicable regulatory
requirements relating to our operations including</font> all applicable noise
level regulations.&#160; AirNet is working
proactively with various local governments to minimize noise issues; however,
future noise pollution regulations could require the replacement of several of
our aircraft.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">6</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='6',FILE='C:\C2\ahanson\8404_4\t_1322525\j8404_10k.htm',USER='ahanson',CD='Mar 26 15:16 2003' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Seasonality</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">See
&#147;Item 7:&#160; Management&#146;s Discussion and
Analysis of Financial Condition and Results of Operations&#148; under the heading
&#147;Seasonality and Variability in Quarterly Results&#148;.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Competition</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The air and ground
courier industry is highly competitive.&#160;
AirNet&#146;s primary competitor in the transportation of cancelled checks is
the Federal Reserve&#146;s Check Relay Network. The actions of the Federal Reserve
are regulated by the Monetary Control Act, which requires the Federal Reserve
to price its services at actual cost plus a set percentage private sector
adjustment factor. AirNet believes that the purpose of the Monetary Control Act
is to curtail the possibility of predatory pricing by the Federal Reserve when
it competes with the private sector. No assurance beyond the remedies of law
can be given that the Federal Reserve will comply with the Monetary Control
Act.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the private sector,
there are a large number of smaller, regional carriers that transport cancelled
checks, none with a significant interstate market share. The two largest private
sector air couriers, Federal Express Corporation (&#147;FedEx&#148;) and United Parcel
Service (&#147;UPS&#148;), both carry cancelled checks where the deadlines being pursued
fit into their existing system, but this has not represented a significant
market share of this industry market to date. AirNet provides customized
service for our customer base, often with later pick-ups and earlier deliveries
than the large, national couriers provide.&#160;
Both FedEx and UPS utilize AirNet&#146;s transportation network for certain
situations where they require customized service.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet competes with
commercial airlines and numerous other carriers in its Express delivery
business.&#160; AirNet estimates its market
share in this industry at less than 1%.&#160;
AirNet believes that this market represents a significant expansion
opportunity for ultra time-critical shipments requiring later pick-ups or
earlier deliveries than are typically provided by major integrators and freight
forwarders.&#160; AirNet believes that we are
in an excellent position to leverage the use of our unique air network system,
our proprietary information technology and our historically high on-time
performance level to compete in this market.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">In the passenger charter
business, AirNet competes with other owner/operators of small business jets and
charter brokers.&#160; We believe our
nationwide network of maintenance and related support facilities provides added
flexibility in deploying and servicing the passenger charter aircraft fleet to
meet customer demands.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Environmental matters</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet believes that
compliance with applicable laws and regulations governing environmental matters
have not had, and are not expected to have, a material effect on AirNet&#146;s
capital expenditures, operations or competitive position.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Employees</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">As of December 31, 2002
AirNet employed 1,045 persons.&#160; AirNet&#146;s
employees are not represented by any union or covered by any collective
bargaining agreement.&#160; AirNet has
experienced no work stoppages and believes that our relationship with employees
is good.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item2"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 2</font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;"> - PROPERTIES</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Operating facilities</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet owns its corporate
and operational headquarters at 3939 International Gateway in Columbus,
Ohio.&#160; The complex has 80,000 square
feet and sits on land owned by the Port Authority of Columbus.&#160; AirNet has a 25-year land lease with the
Port Authority, which expires on December 31, 2009 and contains a 20-year
renewal option.&#160; AirNet&#146;s headquarters
is currently used for operations, training, aircraft maintenance, vehicle
maintenance and general and administrative functions.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet leases additional
space at 4700 East Fifth Avenue, also located on Port Authority of Columbus
land.&#160; The space is used for
administrative support personnel.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operates at
approximately 40 additional locations throughout the country. These locations,
which are leased from unrelated third parties, generally include office space
and/or a section of the lessor&#146;s hangar or ramp.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">7</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

</font>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Fleet</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>


<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><sup><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></sup>Maximum payload in
pounds for a one-hour flight plus required fuel reserves.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><sup><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></sup>Maximum range in
nautical miles, assuming zero wind, full fuel and maximum payload.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(3)</font><sup><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></sup>Maximum speed in
knots, assuming maximum payload</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(4)</font><sup><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font></sup>Includes aircraft
grounded until replacement engines or repair parts become available (seven as
of December<sup>&#160; </sup>31<sup>, </sup>2002).</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">An inventory of spare
engines and parts is maintained for each aircraft type.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Learjet 35 is among the fastest, most reliable and most fuel-efficient small
jet aircraft available in the world and meets all Stage Three noise
requirements currently being implemented across the country.&#160; The Learjet 25 is a smaller jet aircraft
with slightly smaller payload and range capabilities.&#160; The Learjet 25 is not Stage Three compliant and likely will be
phased out of scheduled operations in 2003.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Cessna Caravan Super Cargomaster aircraft is a turbo-prop aircraft that travels
at a similar speed to the Piper Aerostar aircraft previously in the fleet, but
with over four times the payload of the Aerostar.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The
Piper Navajo, Beech Baron and Cessna 310 are twin-engine piston aircraft.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Passenger
charter aircraft</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

information about our passenger charter aircraft fleet as of December 31, 2002:</font></p>

  </td>
  <td width="11%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#cceeff" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:11.0%;">
  <p align="right" style="font-size:1.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:right;">&nbsp;</p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" bgcolor="#cceeff" style="background:#CCEEFF;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:1.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>
  </td>
 </tr>
</table>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="1" width="25%" noshade color="black" align="left">

</font></div>


<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(1)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum number of persons</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(2)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum range in
nautical miles, assuming zero wind, full fuel and full payload.</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(3)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Maximum speed in knots,
assuming full payload</p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt .5in;text-indent:-.25in;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">(4)</font><font size="1" style="font-size:3.0pt;">&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160; </font>Includes one aircraft
operated under a management agreement</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">An inventory of parts is
maintained for each type of Learjet.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The Learjet 60 is a
midsize business jet with transcontinental range and</font> meets all Stage Three noise requirements.</p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">8</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

</font></div>

<font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">
<!-- SEQ.=1,FOLIO='8',FILE='C:\C2\ahanson\8404_4\t_1322525\j8404_10k.htm',USER='ahanson',CD='Mar 26 15:16 2003' -->
<br clear="all" style="page-break-before:always;">
</font>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><i><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-style:italic;">Vehicles</font></i></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet operates a fleet
of approximately 125 ground transportation vehicles.&#160;&#160; Vehicles range in size from passenger cars to full sized
vans.&#160; AirNet also rents lightweight
trucks for certain weekend ground routes.&#160;
In 2001, AirNet entered into a leasing agreement with a third party
provider and began replacing owned vehicles with leased vehicles, as
replacement became necessary.&#160; AirNet
leased 81 vehicles as of December 31, 2002 and intends to lease all ground
transportation vehicles as replacement becomes necessary.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item3"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 3</font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;"> - LEGAL
PROCEEDINGS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">There are no pending
legal proceedings involving AirNet other than routine litigation incidental to
our business. In the opinion of AirNet&#146;s management, these proceedings should
not, individually or in the aggregate, have a material adverse effect on
AirNet&#146;s results of operations or financial condition.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item4"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 4</font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;"> -
SUBMISSION OF MATTERS TO A VOTE OF SECURITY HOLDERS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">No matters were submitted
to a vote of security holders during the fourth quarter of 2002.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">9</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<hr size="2" width="100%" noshade color="gray" align="left">

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Joel E. Biggerstaff has
served as AirNet&#146;s Chairman of the Board since August 2001, Chief Executive
Officer since April 2000, and as President and Chief Operating Officer since
August 1999.&#160; Prior to joining AirNet,
Mr. Biggerstaff served as President of the Southern Region of Corporate Express
Delivery Systems, a national expedited distribution service, from February 1998
through July 1999.&#160; From September 1996
through February 1998, Mr. Biggerstaff provided transportation consulting
services and prior to September 1996, he held various positions within Ryder
System, Inc., including Regional Vice President and General Manager.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">William R. Sumser has
served AirNet as the Chief Financial Officer since January 1, 2000, as
Treasurer since March 1999, and as the Vice President, Finance and Secretary
since March 1996.&#160; He also served as
Controller from 1988 through 1999.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Jeffery B. Harris has
served AirNet as Senior Vice President, Sales since May 2000.&#160; Mr. Harris served as Vice President, Sales
in the banking division from October 1997 to May 2000.&#160; Prior to joining AirNet in June 1996 as the
Relationship Manager for Banking Sales, Mr. Harris served as Vice President and
Senior Transit Product Manager for Mellon Bank, N.A. from 1994 to 1996.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Craig A. Leach has served
as Vice President, Information Systems since January 2000.&#160; Mr. Leach established AirNet&#146;s Information
Systems Department in 1985 and was named Director of Information Systems in
1996.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Stephen K. Lister was
appointed Vice President, Airline Operations in February 2001.&#160; Mr. Lister has served AirNet in a variety of
capacities since 1982.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Wynn D. Peterson, CFA,
has served as Vice President, Corporate Development since February 2000.&#160; He joined AirNet in 1997 as Manager of
Corporate Development.&#160; Prior to joining
AirNet, Mr. Peterson served as a Portfolio Manager for Deseret Mutual from 1993
to 1997.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">Kendall W. Wright has
served as Vice President, Operations since 2001.&#160; He served as Vice President, Sales from 1988 through 2000.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">10</font></p>


<div style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">

<p align="center" style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;text-align:center;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item5"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 5</font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;"> - MARKET
FOR REGISTRANT&#146;S COMMON EQUITY AND RELATED STOCKHOLDER MATTERS</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">The common shares of
AirNet Systems, Inc. trade on the New York Stock Exchange under the symbol
&#147;ANS&#148;.&#160; The table below sets forth the
high and low sales prices of the common shares reported for the periods
indicated.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">AirNet has not paid any
dividends on our common shares and does not intend to pay any dividends in the
foreseeable future.&#160; AirNet anticipates
using future earnings to finance operations and future growth and development.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">On March 20, 2003, there
were approximately 2,000 holders of AirNet common shares, based upon the number
of holders of record and the number of individual participants in certain
security position listings.</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="font-size:10.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><a name="Item6"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">ITEM 6</font></b></a><b><font style="font-weight:bold;"> -
SELECTED FINANCIAL DATA</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;font-weight:bold;">Statement of Operations Data</font></b></p>

<p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><font size="2" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:10.0pt;">&nbsp;</font></p>

<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%" style="border-collapse:collapse;width:100.0%;">
 <tr>
  <td width="39%" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:39.0%;">
  <p style="margin:0in 0in .0001pt;"><b><font size="1" face="Times New Roman" style="font-size:8.0pt;font-weight:bold;">(in
  thousands, except per share data)</font></b></p>
  </td>
  <td width="2%" valign="bottom" style="padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:2.0%;">
  <p style="font-size:1.0pt;margin:0in 0in .0001pt;">&nbsp;</p>
  </td>
  <td width="58%" colspan="14" valign="bottom" style="border:none;border-bottom:solid windowtext .5pt;padding:0in 0in 0in 0in;width:58.0%;">
